{The 2\C bid was Stayman, so you bid your \Hs.

Partner takes the direct approach and puts you in slam.

South plays 6\H. West leads the \CQ. West finds their best lead, exposing your \C loser right off the bat.

Loser List: \S = 0 : \H = 1 : \D = 0 : \C = 1 :: Total = 2

If you can guess the \H finesse correctly you will make 7, discarding dummy's \C loser on the fourth \D. But if you guess wrong they will immediately set you with a \C trick. 

There is a better way - one that combines two chances. Win the \CA. Then play your \HA and \HK. If the \HQ happens to fall, pull the last trump and run your winners.

If the \HQ <b>DOESN'T</b> fall, (she won't of course), switch to \Ds. On the fourth round of \Ds discard dummy's \C, whether it is ruffed with the \HQ or not.

If you knew to play the East for the \HQ then you wouldn't need this improved plan.

But playing the deal as described will win whenever the \HQ is doubleton, <b>OR</b> when the player with the protected \HQ holds at least 3 \Ds.

Pretty good odds, better than the going rate for finesses, which is 50% off.

There was an alternate plan, just as good. After taking the two top trumps, run the \Ss, discarding two \Cs from your hand. As you see, either would have worked.}
[Play "W"]CQ

